##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.App.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

App.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.App.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

### CloudBackend <a name="CloudBackend" id="cdktf.CloudBackend"></a>

The Cloud Backend synthesizes a {@link https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/cloud/settings#the-cloud-block cloud block}. The cloud block is a nested block within the top-level terraform settings block. It specifies which Terraform Cloud workspaces to use for the current working directory. The cloud block only affects Terraform CLI's behavior. When Terraform Cloud uses a configuration that contains a cloud block - for example, when a workspace is configured to use a VCS provider directly - it ignores the block and behaves according to its own workspace settings.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.CloudBackend.Initializer"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

new CloudBackend(Construct Scope, CloudBackendConfig Props);
```

| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------- | ----------------- |

| <code><a href="#cdktf.CloudBackend.Initializer.parameter.props">Props</a></code> | <code><a href="#cdktf.CloudBackendConfig">CloudBackendConfig</a></code> | _No description._ |

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.ConsulBackend.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

ConsulBackend.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.ConsulBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsTerraformElement` <a name="IsTerraformElement" id="cdktf.ConsulBackend.isTerraformElement"></a>

### DataResource <a name="DataResource" id="cdktf.DataResource"></a>

The DataResource implements the standard resource lifecycle, but does not directly take any other actions.

You can use the DataResource resource without requiring or configuring a provider.

The DataResource resource is useful for storing values which need to follow a manage resource lifecycle, and for triggering provisioners when there is no other logical managed resource in which to place them.

It requires Terraform 1.4 or later.

It is also possible to generate these bindings by adding "terraform.io/builtin/terraform" to the "terraformProviders" key in your cdktf.json file and running "cdktf get".

https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/resources/terraform-data

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.DataResource.Initializer"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

new DataResource(Construct Scope, string Id, DataConfig Config = null);
```

| **Name**                                                                           | **Type**                                                | **Description**                              |
| ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.DataResource.Initializer.parameter.scope">Scope</a></code>   | <code>Constructs.Construct</code>                       | The scope in which to define this construct. |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.DataResource.Initializer.parameter.id">Id</a></code>         | <code>string</code>                                     | The scoped construct ID.                     |
| <code><a href="#cdktf.DataResource.Initializer.parameter.config">Config</a></code> | <code><a href="#cdktf.DataConfig">DataConfig</a></code> | _No description._                            |

---

##### `Scope`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="Scope" id="cdktf.DataResource.Initializer.parameter.scope"></a>

- _Type:_ Constructs.Construct

The scope in which to define this construct.

---

##### `Id`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="Id" id="cdktf.DataResource.Initializer.parameter.id"></a>

Must be unique amongst siblings in the same scope

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataResource.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataResource.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteState.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataTerraformRemoteState.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteState.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateConsul.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataTerraformRemoteStateConsul.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateConsul.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateHttp.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateOss.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.DataTerraformRemoteStateS3.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.GcsBackend.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

GcsBackend.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.GcsBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.LocalBackend.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

LocalBackend.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.LocalBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.RemoteBackend.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

RemoteBackend.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.RemoteBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### ~~`IsConstruct`~~ <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.SwiftBackend.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

SwiftBackend.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.SwiftBackend.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformDataSource.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformDataSource.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformDataSource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformHclModule.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformHclModule.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformHclModule.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

### TerraformModule <a name="TerraformModule" id="cdktf.TerraformModule"></a>

- _Implements:_ <a href="#cdktf.ITerraformDependable">ITerraformDependable</a>

TerraformModule can be used to reference a local terraform module or a module from the Terraform Registry.

It should be used if you can not use generated bindings for the module as you would get by adding the module
to your cdktf.json files "terraformModules" array and running cdktf get.

This class is not creating a Terraform module to be used outside of CDKTF.
If you want to bundle certain resources together like you would do with a Terraform module,
you should use Constructs instead, see http://cdk.tf/constructs for more details.

#### Initializers <a name="Initializers" id="cdktf.TerraformModule.Initializer"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

new TerraformModule(Construct Scope, string Id, TerraformModuleConfig Options);
```

| **Name**                                                                                | **Type**                                                                      | **Description**   |

| <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformModule.Initializer.parameter.options">Options</a></code> | <code><a href="#cdktf.TerraformModuleConfig">TerraformModuleConfig</a></code> | _No description._ |

##### `AddOverride` <a name="AddOverride" id="cdktf.TerraformModule.addOverride"></a>

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformModule.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformModule.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformModule.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsTerraformElement` <a name="IsTerraformElement" id="cdktf.TerraformModule.isTerraformElement"></a>

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformRemoteState.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformRemoteState.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformRemoteState.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformResource.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformResource.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformResource.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---

##### `IsConstruct` <a name="IsConstruct" id="cdktf.TerraformVariable.isConstruct"></a>

```csharp
using HashiCorp.Cdktf;

TerraformVariable.IsConstruct(object X);
```

Checks if `x` is a construct.

Use this method instead of `instanceof` to properly detect `Construct`
instances, even when the construct library is symlinked.

Explanation: in JavaScript, multiple copies of the `constructs` library on
disk are seen as independent, completely different libraries. As a
consequence, the class `Construct` in each copy of the `constructs` library
is seen as a different class, and an instance of one class will not test as
`instanceof` the other class. `npm install` will not create installations
like this, but users may manually symlink construct libraries together or
use a monorepo tool: in those cases, multiple copies of the `constructs`
library can be accidentally installed, and `instanceof` will behave
unpredictably. It is safest to avoid using `instanceof`, and using
this type-testing method instead.

###### `X`<sup>Required</sup> <a name="X" id="cdktf.TerraformVariable.isConstruct.parameter.x"></a>

- _Type:_ object

Any object.

---
